ef="cc12487-2"/></fig><p>When compared with Vt of 6 ml/kg, Vt 4 significantly decreased &#x00394;NAT and this effect was consistent in all patients (Table <xref ref-type="table" rid="T4">4</xref>, Figure <xref ref-type="fig" rid="F3">3A</xref>). Delta HIT and HITmax also decreased significantly with Vt 4 ml/kg (Table <xref ref-type="table" rid="T4">4</xref> Figure <xref ref-type="fig" rid="F3">3B</xref>). There was no change in NATmax between both Vts (Figure <xref ref-type="fig" rid="F3">3C</xref>). We found no relation between ARDS severity and &#x00394;NAT or HIT max.</p><table-wrap id="T4" position="float"><label>Table 4</label><caption><p>Analysis of density fractions of the lungs.</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th/><th align="center" colspan="2">Tidal volume</th><th/></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td/><td align="center"><bold>Vt 4</bold></td><td align="center"><bold>Vt 6</bold></td><td align="center"><bold>
